Interpretation:
  Remove a negative simple-current factor e_k from an odd-sign remainder.
  The remaining product has even exchange parity and coefficient matrix h.
  Reattaching the negative e_k makes the target-k partial coefficient
    h_(0,0)-h_(k,k).
  The mode enumerates every multiset with labels 1,...,k-1, every even
  minus mask, and at most seven remaining factors.  It checks h_(0,0)>=0
  and h_(0,0)-h_(k,k)>=0 exactly with arbitrary-precision integers.
  An active case has h_(k,k)>0.  No active equality occurred in this domain;
  the smallest active slack was two.  Complementary factor assignments pair
  equal diagonal contributions for every nonempty even-sign remainder, so
  both diagonal coefficients and the slack are even.  Thus two is merely the
  smallest possible strict integral gap.  This is bounded evidence, not a
  proof of strictness or of diagonal dominance outside the tested domain.

The count-zero sector is already active in 2,310 words.  Thus the first
unproved layer of the wall target is the unsigned inequality
  sum_S m_0(S)m_0(S^c) >= sum_S m_k(S)m_k(S^c),
not a cancellation phenomenon requiring two or more remaining minus signs.
